One of my favorite photographs of all time taken by @danielkrieger . 

This image is of one of the oldest tenured servers coming through the kitchen doors one last time on the final night at Chin Chin . A restaurant that had been a staple for over 30 years in NYC . 

The photo is so powerful when you think about how many trips this gentleman took through those doors over the years and the countless guests that he was able to serve and the infinite amount of memories he collected. 
The restaurants  we come to every day becomes our home , the people in them our family. We do something every day that directly affects the days of others in a positive way. For that I'm grateful. 🍀

Almost 13 years ago I walked into this broken down building looking for a place to make BBQ and it was love at first site !  The walls were caving in , it was flooded , saw dust covered all the walls and the ceilings were coming down but something  about it just called me. 
I could literally see what it would look like , smell like and feel like. 
But , Why in the world would a kid from Flatbush Brooklyn who was in a completely different profession want to open a BBQ restaurant in a part of Brooklyn where not many people traveled too and where there is no BBQ culture ? Every friend and family member thought I was insane and I didn't blame them. A few years later after having to rebuild after Hurricane Sandy destroyed our community we finally opened our doors. With 14 team members  on a rain soaked day much like today the dream had become a reality. 
That day I was in the pit area carving and had no idea that our room had completely flooded. I walked over to see what had happened and our neighbors had their pants rolled up and were pushing the water out of the building.  I knew that day I was in the best community in the world and we would be just fine. My friend Barry Omeara  who  owned the Bait and Tackle , one of the best bars in history told me in his best Irish brogue. "Billy , welcome to Red Hook , this flood is your baptism.  I am forever grateful for every staff member who has put their blood , sweat and tears into this dream. And to the most ferociously loyal , dedicated guests that took a chance on the kid from Brooklyn , you have Blessed me beyond anything I could have ever dreamed.  Today we celebrate as we did 10 years ago in the rain , praying for the gift of another 10 years and beyond. 
Forever grateful 
Billy 🍀
